 1274":"omkring 1274","Granston, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Granston, Pembrokeshire, Wales","Wales, United Kingdom":"Wales, United Kingdom","Poyston, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Poyston, Pembrokeshire, Wales","Haverfordwest, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Haverfordwest, Pembrokeshire, Wales"},"nl":{"1275–":"1275–Overleden","1275–Female":"1275–Overleden","1270–Male":"1270–Overleden","1305–1365":"1305–1365","1245–Male":"1245–Overleden","1245–Female":"1245–Overleden","1305":"1305","1245":"1245","1365":"1365","1275":"1275","1270":"1270","about 1274":"circa 1274","Granston, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Granston, Pembrokeshire, Wales","Wales, United Kingdom":"Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Poyston, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Poyston, Pembrokeshire, Wales","Haverfordwest, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Haverfordwest, Pembrokeshire, Wales"},"en":{"1275–":"1275–Deceased","1275–Female":"1275–Deceased","1270–Male":"1270–Deceased","1305–1365":"1305–1365","1245–Male":"1245–Deceased","1245–Female":"1245–Deceased","1305":"1305","1245":"1245","1365":"1365","1275":"1275","1270":"1270","about 1274":"about 1274","Granston, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Granston, Pembrokeshire, Wales","Wales, United Kingdom":"Wales, United Kingdom","Poyston, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Poyston, Pembrokeshire, Wales","Haverfordwest, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Haverfordwest, Pembrokeshire, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Horton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Staffordshire and Warwickshire): habitational name from one or other of the many places so called, such as those in Berkshire, Buckinghamshire, Dorset, Gloucestershire, Herefordshire, Northamptonshire, Shropshire, Somerset, Staffordshire, Wiltshire, and Yorkshire. Most of the placenames derive from Old English <i>horh</i> or <i>horu</i> ‘dirt, filth’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’, though some may have different origins, including Horton in Gloucestershire, which may derive from Old English <i>heorot</i> ‘hart, stag’ + <i>tūn</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Hortin","meanings":["English: variant of   Horton  ."]},{"name":"Horten","meanings":["English: variant of   Horton  .","Norwegian: habitational name from any of several farms named Horten, from an unattested word denoting ‘uneven, hard and lumpy soil’."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Agnes Horton was born in 1275, in Granston, Pembrokeshire, Wales, her father, Sir Philip Horton, was 31 and her mother, Horton, was 31. She had at least 1 son with Sir Thomas Picton. She died in Haverfordwest, Pembrokeshire, Wales."},"et":{"1275–":"1275–Surnud","1275–Female":"1275–Surnud","1270–Male":"1270–Surnud","1305–1365":"1305–1365","1245–Male":"1245–Surnud","1245–Female":"1245–Surnud","1305":"1305","1245":"1245","1365":"1365","1275":"1275","1270":"1270","about 1274":"umbes 1274","Granston, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Granston, Pembrokeshire, Wales","Wales, United Kingdom":"Wales, United Kingdom","Poyston, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Poyston, Pembrokeshire, Wales","Haverfordwest, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Haverfordwest, Pembrokeshire, Wales"},"fi":{"1275–":"1275–Kuollut","1275–Female":"1275–Kuollut","1270–Male":